🧠 OS Concept 1: Load Balancing
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Distribute workload across multiple servers/resources.

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Supermarket 🛒

Instead of one billing counter:

👉 many counters share customers.

⚙️ Why Needed?

Without load balancing:

❌ one server overloaded
❌ slow response
❌ crashes

⚙️ Example
Users
 ↓
Load Balancer
 ↙   ↓   ↘
S1   S2   S3
🔗 Connection to Scalability

Load balancing helps:

✔ scalability
✔ availability
✔ reliability

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why use load balancing?

👉 To distribute traffic and avoid server overload.

🧠 Memory Trick
Load balancing = divide work evenly
🧠 OS Concept 2: Fault Tolerance

🔥 Very important system-design concept.

1️⃣ Simple Idea

System continues working even if some parts fail.

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Car with spare tire 🚗

Even if one tire fails:

👉 journey continues.

⚙️ How Systems Achieve It
Backup servers
Replication
Redundancy
Failover systems
🔗 Connection

Used in:

cloud systems
banking systems
emergency apps
🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why is fault tolerance important?

👉 Ensures system reliability and availability during failures.

🧠 Memory Trick
Fault tolerance = survive failures
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Cache Optimization in Real Systems
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Good programs use cache efficiently.

Example

Sequential memory access:

arr[0], arr[1], arr[2]

✔ cache friendly

Poor Access
arr[0], arr[5000], arr[2]

❌ cache misses increase

Why Important?

Cache miss = slow memory access.

🔗 Connection

Uses:

👉 spatial locality

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why sequential access is faster?

👉 Due to spatial locality and better cache usage.

🧠 Memory Trick
Nearby data = cache friendly
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Bottleneck Analysis

🔥 Product-company favorite.

1️⃣ Simple Idea

Bottleneck = slowest part limiting system performance.

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Traffic jam caused by narrow bridge 🌉

Even if roads are fast:

👉 bridge limits speed.

Examples in Computer Systems
Slow disk
Memory latency
Network delay
CPU overload
🔗 Connection

Von Neumann bottleneck was one example.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why bottleneck analysis important?

👉 Because improving non-bottleneck parts may not improve overall performance.

🧠 Memory Trick
System speed limited by slowest part
